 for bestpractices and # Landing Page Prompt for AI Development Tool

Below is a complete, actionable prompt to deliver a production-ready Landing Page (public marketing page) for Gbox360, with alignment to the provided project context, design system, and strict runtime safety rules. The prompt is structured to guide an AI development tool to generate frontend, backend, and integration assets, with precise acceptance criteria and testing guidance.

---

## Landing Page

### Overview
Build a public-facing Landing Page for Gbox360 that clearly communicates the Investor Perception Index (IPI) value proposition to prospective users. The page should drive sign-ups and demo requests via prominent CTAs, showcase a preview of the IPI experience (sample IPI snapshot), outline the key features, and present trust marks (auditability). The design must be modern, enterprise-grade, accessible, and consistent with the Gbox360 design language. All interactive elements must be accessible, performant, and resilient to null/undefined data.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A public marketing landing page that explains Gbox360’s value proposition, with clear CTAs to sign up or request a demo.
- Visual storytelling sections: hero with primary and secondary CTAs, a “How It Works” three-step graphic, a static Sample IPI Snapshot, Feature Highlights, Trust & Compliance, and a Footer with helpful links.

Goals:
- Convert visitors into sign-ups or demo requests.
- Demonstrate credibility with a sample IPI snapshot, auditability statements, and placeholder logos/quotes.

Connected features (from PROJECT CONTEXT) to showcase or hint at deeper flows:
- The platform’s conceptual IPI and narrative model, without performing live data loads on this landing page.
- Internal emphasis on auditability, provenance, and governance signals that align with the later Signup/Login flows.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Hero Section: Bold value proposition, 1-line subtitle, primary CTA (Sign up / Request demo) as bold filled button, secondary CTA (Explore sample IPI) as a secondary action.
- How It Works: 3-step graphic illustrating Ingest → Canonicalize → Explain IPI, with concise copy and intuitive icons.
- Sample IPI Snapshot: Static, visually rich tile showing IPI score, directional indicator (up/down), and a top-narrative summary.
- Feature Highlights: Cards detailing NarrativeEvent model, audit export, drill-downs, governance roadmap; each card has a title, supporting text, and optional mini-CTA or tag chips.
- Trust & Compliance: Brief auditability statement, data retention snippet, placeholder customer logos/quotes.
- Footer: Navigation links (About, Help, Privacy Policy, Terms of Service) and a contact form (non-blocking) for inquiries.
- Visual guidance: Clean card surfaces, ample whitespace, subtle elevation, and careful alignment with the given color palette and typography.

Engineering constraints:
- Implement purely with frontend assets and static content for the landing page.
- Do not wire actual live APIs for this page; the page should gracefully render if data is missing or null.
- Ensure all dynamic data paths (if any) are guarded with null/undefined safety checks as described in the “Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety” section.

---

## Components to Build
- LandingHero
  - Props: title, subtitle, ctaPrimary, ctaSecondary
  - Behavior: responsive layout; primary CTA triggers sign-up flow; secondary triggers demo tour/exploration; accessibility: aria-labels, keyboard accessible.
- HowItWorks
  - 3 StepCard components: Ingest, Canonicalize, Explain IPI
  - Each StepCard includes icon, short copy, and optional supporting micro-copy.
- SampleIPISnapshot
  - Static, non-live data: score badge, direction indicator, top three narrative summary items.
  - Visuals: tile with a compact mini chart placeholder (SVG) and a tagline.
- FeatureCard
  - Props: title, description, tag (optional), CTA (optional)
  - Layout: image/thumbnail at top, then title, copy, and a bottom-aligned CTA or tag chips in accent color.
- TrustCompliance
  - Content: auditability statement, data retention snippet, logos/quotes area (placeholders).
- FooterLinks
  - Simple footer with policy links and a small contact form (name, email, message) that is client-side only for demonstration.
- Shared UI primitives
  - Button (Primary, Secondary, Ghost), Card, Chip, Icon, Grid/Container, Typography presets (H1, H2, Body, Caption).

Implementation notes:
- All components must guard against null/undefined values before rendering lists or invoking array methods.
- Use data ?? [] patterns and Array.isArray() guards where lists are present.
- Ensure defaults are in place for any optional data.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React with TypeScript (recommended for strict types).
- Routing: Public route for Landing Page; ensure no auth gating on this page.
- State management: Local UI state only; no global store required for the landing page.
- Accessibility: All interactive elements keyboard accessible; visible focus states; color contrast compliant (AA/AAA where feasible).
- UI behavior:
  - Responsive, grid-based layout using a 12-column grid with generous vertical rhythm (48–64px between major sections).
  - Card surfaces with subtle borders (#E5E7EB) and soft shadows; hover lift on cards.
  - CTA interactions: hover/focus color changes using the provided accent palette.
- Data safety:
  - If any dynamic copy or lists are used, guard them with (data ?? []) and Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : [] patterns.
- Styling:
  - Implement using CSS Modules, styled-components, or a CSS-in-JS solution consistent with the project.
  - Typography and spacing must adhere to the provided design system: Inter/system-ui-like font, sizes, weights, line-heights, and a 12-column responsive grid.
- Visual assets:
  - Use inline SVG icons for hero steps and sample IPI visualization placeholders (no external data loads).
  - Ensure assets scale for high-DPI (SVGs render crisp).

### Backend
- Not required for Landing Page; no API calls needed. If placeholders for marketing content data are introduced, ensure they are optional and safely handled (e.g., static defaults).

### Integration
- Data flow: None for this page; the integration layer is about design-system consistency and safe data handling if content is replaced by CMS-driven data in the future.
- Ensure that if a CMS provides content, code paths gracefully fall back to defaults with proper null checks (e.g., content?.sections?.length ?? 0).

---

## User Experience Flow
- Visitor lands on the Landing Page.
- Hero communicates value proposition with two primary actions:
  - Sign up: opens sign-up flow or navigates to Signup Page (consider modal or route).
  - Request demo: navigates to a demo request flow or modal.
- Visitor can click "Explore sample IPI" to view the Sample IPI Snapshot section and related content.
- User can scroll to How It Works to understand ingestion, canonicalization, and explanation of IPI.
- Visitor may review Feature Highlights for governance and auditability capabilities.
- Visitor reviews Trust & Compliance; footer provides policy links and contact form.
- If user interacts with the contact form in the footer, ensure no submission is required for this landing page prototype (client-side validation and a success state).

---

## Technical Specifications

Data Models:
- No persistent data models required for the landing page.
- If content is externalized, define a minimal CMS-like schema:
  - PageSection: id, type (hero, how-it-works, sample-ipi, features, trust, footer), content object.
  - FeatureCard: id, title, description, tag, ctaLabel, ctaLink.
  - SnapshotCard: id, score, direction, topNarratives[]. Each narrative: id, text, weight.
- Runtime safety: All lists default to [] and all optional properties are guarded with defaults.

API Endpoints:
- None required for the landing page prototype. If you plan to fetch content from a CMS in the future, endpoints can be stubbed:
  - GET /api/landing-content -> { sections: PageSection[] }
  - GET /api/landing-snapshot -> { score: number, direction: 'up'|'down', topNarratives: string[] }

Security:
- None required for static marketing page. If integrating a CMS or forms, ensure form submission endpoints are protected and use CSRF tokens as needed in production.

Validation:
- Client-side validations for the footer contact form if enabled (name non-empty, email format, message length). All arrays/collections must be validated with guards as per runtime safety rules.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The Landing Page renders a hero with title, subtitle, and two CTAs that are keyboard accessible and visually distinct.
- [ ] The How It Works section shows three steps with icons and copy, using a 12-column responsive grid.
- [ ] The Sample IPI Snapshot tile renders with score, direction indicator, and a top narrative summary, using static data and safe guards for null values.
- [ ] All array-based renderings guard against null/undefined: (data ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : [].
- [ ] All text content uses the specified typography scale and color palette; visual design tokens align with the provided color palette.
- [ ] No API calls are made on initial render; any dynamic data is safely optional and defaults to static content.
- [ ] Accessibility: all interactive elements have aria-labels, focus states visible, and sufficient color contrast.

---

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Align with the 12-column grid, generous whitespace, and consistent card-based layout.
- Use the exact color tokens provided for backgrounds, text, borders, surfaces, and accents.
- Implement the typographic hierarchy for H1/H2/body/meta/Numerics as described.
- Maintain visual emphasis on primary CTAs and trust signals.

